        enDetailContent: "A BUSINESS RULE is a policy, directive, standard, or rule that defines or constrains some aspect of business processes. It is NOT a software requirement by nature, but serves as a source of requirements.\n\nCLASSIFICATION OF BUSINESS RULES:\n\n1. FACTS — incontrovertible truths about the business\nExample: 'Every order has a creation date'\n\n2. CONSTRAINTS — limits on what is possible\nExample: 'Customer credit limit cannot exceed $50,000'\n\n3. ACTION ENABLERS — conditions that trigger actions\nExample: 'If an order exceeds $10,000 — manager approval is required'\n\n4. INFERENCES — logical consequences\nExample: 'If a customer places 5 orders — they become VIP'\n\n5. COMPUTATIONS — formulas and algorithms\nExample: 'VAT = order amount × 20%'\n\nDOCUMENTATION:\nBusiness rules are stored separately from software requirements — usually in a business rules catalog. Each rule has a unique identifier, description, source, and status.",
